# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: matthew-richardson-footballer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] The **1992 AFL draft** is the annual draft of talented players by Australian rules football teams that participate in the main competition of that sport, the Australian Football League.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] It consisted of the main national draft, the pre-season draft and the trade period.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] In 1992 there were 124 picks to be drafted between 15 teams in the main national draft.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] There was a mid-year draft held during the 1992 season.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] Players recruited in this draft were able to take their places in their AFL clubs in the latter part of the 1992 season, although not all chose to do so.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] The 1992 draft suffered from three high-profile cases of draft tampering involving highly rated South Australian players: No.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] However, this action was contrary to the rules, as it circumvented the fairness of the draft.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] The most serious offence was by Chalmers, who had contacted most clubs in an effort to ensure that only Collingwood would draft him.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] He was fined $30,000, and was made ineligible to play for Collingwood for three years; he never played a senior game for Collingwood, but later played for Adelaide and Port Adelaide.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] McKay and Pyman, who had warned only the AFL's struggling clubs (Sydney, Brisbane Bears, Richmond and Fitzroy) against drafting them, but had not contrived to end up at a specific club, were fined only $10,000 and were permitted to continue playing for their new clubs.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1992-afl-draft] Brisbane Bears zone selection Nathan Buckley and the North Melbourne Football Club were also forced to defend accusations that they had come to a draft-tampering agreement for Buckley to later be traded to North Melbourne, but after a long and costly legal battle both parties were found not guilty.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-rising-star] The **Norwich AFL Rising Star** award is given annually to a standout young player in the Australian Football League.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-rising-star] This was the first season the medal was awarded and the award went to Nathan Buckley in his debut, and only, season at the Brisbane Bears.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-rising-star] Every round, an Australian Football League rising star nomination is given to a standout young player.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-rising-star] To be eligible for the award, a player must be under 21 on January 1 of that year, have played 10 or fewer senior games and not been suspended during the season.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-rising-star] At the end of the year, one of the 22 nominees is the winner of award.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-rising-star] The nominated players from 1993 are considered to be one of the most successful of all years.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-season] The **1993 AFL season** was the 97th season of the Australian Football League (AFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Australia, which was known as the Victorian Football League until 1989.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-season] The season featured fifteen clubs, ran from 26 March until 25 September, and comprised a 20-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top six clubs.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-season] The premiership was won by the Essendon Football Club for the 15th time, after it defeated Carlton by 44 points in the 1993 AFL Grand Final.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-afl-season] The 1993 Foster's Cup saw Essendon 14.18 (102) defeat Richmond 11.13 (79) in the Grand Final.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-state-of-origin-championships] The **1993 State of Origin Championships**, known formally as the CUB AFL State of Origin championship, was the last Australian rules football series held involving representative teams of all Australian states.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-state-of-origin-championships] It was the first and only such tournament run by the AFL Commission.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-state-of-origin-championships] It was the first tournament to combine territory teams with state teams.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-state-of-origin-championships] Victoria, Tasmania, South Australia and Western Australia played as their own states, while New South Wales combined with Australian Capital Territory and Queensland combined with Northern Territory.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-state-of-origin-championships] The two composite teams gave Queensland and New South Wales the first opportunity to select their teams under State of Origin criteria since the 1988 Bicentennial Carnival, but also meant the end of standalone participation by the two territories.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-state-of-origin-championships] Aided significantly by the small Northern Territory contingent, it was the first successful tournament featuring a side under the banner of Queensland, which defeated Tasmania to win Section Two.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-state-of-origin-championships] South Australia defeated Victoria in the section 1 final by 12 points in front of a crowd of 31,792 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1993-state-of-origin-championships] Queensland–Northern Territory defeated Tasmania in the section 2 final by 34 points in front of a crowd of 9,660, at Bellerive Oval.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1994-afl-season] The **1994 AFL season** was the 98th season of the Australian Football League (AFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Australia, which was known as the Victorian Football League until 1989.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1994-afl-season] The season featured fifteen clubs, ran from 26 March until 1 October, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top eight clubs – an increase from the six clubs which had contested the finals in previous years.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1994-afl-season] The premiership was won by the West Coast Eagles for the second time, after it defeated Geelong by 80 points in the 1994 AFL Grand Final.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1994-afl-season] The second McIntyre "final six" system, which had operated in 1992 and 1993, was replaced by the McIntyre "final eight" system.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1994-afl-season] The McIntyre "final eight" system would be used until 1999 and was then replaced by the AFL’s Amended "final eight" system in 2000.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] The **1995 AFL season** was the 99th season of the Australian Football League (AFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Australia, which was known as the Victorian Football League until 1989.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] The league expanded to sixteen clubs, with the newly established Fremantle Football Club, based in Fremantle, Western Australia, joining the league.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] The season ran from 31 March until 30 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top eight clubs.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] The premiership was won by the Carlton Football Club for the 16th time, after it defeated Geelong by 61 points in the 1995 AFL Grand Final.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] North Melbourne defeated Adelaide 14.9 (93) to 8.15 (63) in the final.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] Tony Lockett kicked both his 100th goal for the season and his 1000th career goal during the Sydney Swans v Fremantle game at the Sydney Cricket Ground.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] The Brisbane Bears vs Essendon Bombers game at the Gabba is the first ever night game in Brisbane.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in green indicate that the team finished the round inside the top 8.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in blue indicates the team finished first on the ladder in that round.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1995-afl-season] Numbers highlighted in red indicates the team finished in last place on the ladder in that round.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] The **1996 AFL season** was the 100th season of the Australian Football League (AFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Australia, which was known as the Victorian Football League until 1989.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] The season featured sixteen clubs and ran from 29 March until 28 September, comprising a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] North Melbourne won the premiership for the third time, after it defeated Sydney by 43 points in the 1996 AFL Grand Final.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] The season was the final season for Fitzroy, a founding member of the VFL/AFL in 1897, and there were several celebrations of the league's centenary throughout the year.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] In the 1996 AFL Lightning Premiership final, Essendon defeated the Brisbane Bears 6.2 (38) to 2.9 (21) at Waverley Park.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] In the 1996 Ansett Australia Cup final, St Kilda defeated Carlton 20.10 (130) to 10.12 (72) at Waverley Park.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] Note: The opening four matches of this round replicated the opening round of the inaugural 1897 VFL season, with Essendon and Geelong playing each other on the day of the 99th anniversary.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] Note: Ben Hart took the mark of the year in Adelaide's win over St Kilda.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] Note: Fitzroy's victory was the last win they had in the AFL before merging.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] NOTE: St Kilda vs Essendon match on Saturday night was disrupted by a power failure during the third quarter, resulting the match being completed the following week on the Tuesday night with 2 12-minutes halves.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] Note: Last game of Fitzroy Lions before merger with Brisbane Bears to become Brisbane Lions.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/1996-afl-season] Rules for classification: 1) points; 2) percentage; 3) number of points for.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] On 4 March 2014, Richardson became a member of the AFL's All Australian selection committee.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Richardson is known for his marking prowess, speed and work rate.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He was the club's key forward through the mid-1990s and the 2000s.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He led the club's goalkicking for thirteen seasons, and was selected in the All-Australian Team three times – in 1996, 1999 and 2008.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Richardson's 800 career goals currently see him ranked second behind Jack Titus at Richmond, and twelfth on the all-time list of AFL/VFL goalkickers.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He also holds the record for most goals kicked without winning a Coleman Medal.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He currently holds the record for the most goals kicked at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Richardson was one of the most popular players in the competition; this was shown when the crowd at the 2008 Brownlow Medal cheered every vote he got.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Mark Robinson from the *Herald Sun* wrote "M.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] I'm sure there wouldn't have been a more popular winner".
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Brendan-Shaw and Don Colleges in Devonport, Tasmania, Richardson was the fourth pick (a father–son selection) in the 1992 AFL draft, and was recruited from Devonport, Tasmania.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He is the son of former Richmond and South Melbourne player Alan "Bull" Richardson.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Combining a 197 centimetre frame with speed and athletic capacity, he was a dominant presence for the Tigers.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] In 1996 he came back strongly, playing all 22 games and finished with 91 goals (49 behinds), earning All Australian selection for the first time.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He sustained another knee injury in the pre-season of 2001, but recovered to play 22 games and kick 59 goals.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Richardson finished with a tally of 65 goals for the season.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] In 2005 he kicked 65 goals again, this time with much more consistency throughout the season.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] In 2007, in the Dreamtime at the 'G match against Essendon, Richardson played the game with a fractured eye socket and broken nose sustained only a week before.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He still managed to kick four goals, and was denied a potentially match-winning fifth when he was penalised for a push-in-the-back against his opponent, Mal Michael.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] In the same year, he won his first ever club best-and-fairest, beating young teammate Nathan Foley by a single vote.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He averaged 15.1 disposals & 9 marks per game, he also kicked 53 goals for the season.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Richardson spent a large part of the 2008 season playing on the wing, rather than in the forward line, which allowed him to have a much larger part in the play than previously.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Although he did not win the club best-and-fairest, he was selected on the bench in the All-Australian team and finished third in the Brownlow Medal, polling 22 total votes.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] The 2008 season saw Richardson take 222 marks for the season, including 21 against Hawthorn in Round 20.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He averaged 18.2 disposals per game, along with 11.1 marks per game, in which lead the entire AFL for the season and finals.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Matthew also managed to kick 48 goals for the season.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] In Round 6, 2009 against Sydney at the SCG, Richardson kicked his 800th and last career goal, becoming the eleventh player to reach the milestone in VFL/AFL history.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Later in the same match, he partially tore his hamstring off the bone; he missed the remainder of the season with the injury, and announced his retirement after the season.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He received a rousing send-off in Round 1, 2010, appearing before the match in Richmond's season opener against Carlton.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Richardson retired in 2009 after 282 senior games for Richmond; he became a Richmond Football Club life member after playing more than 150 games for the club and an Australian Football League life member after playing more than 300 games, including representative and pre-season matches.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] His career tally of 800 goals was the eleventh-highest at the time of his retirement, and it remained so until Lance Franklin passed him in Round 6 of the 2017 season.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Richardson took a total of 2,270 marks during his AFL career, which was the second-highest of any player at the time of his retirement (since the statistic was recorded, starting in 1974).
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Following his retirement at the end of the 2009 AFL Season and during parts of the 2009 AFL Season when he was injured, Richardson was an AFL expert commentator for telecast matches and a panellist on the review show 'One Week at a Time', both Network Ten shows.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] In 2010, Richardson became part of the Seven Network AFL telecast team, initially as a boundary rider and then as a member of the Friday and Saturday night commentary teams, providing expert comments.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He also appears on the Thursday night edition of *Seven News Melbourne*, to preview the weekend's AFL action, and as a panellist on Channel 7's AFL Game Day.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] He also is the colour commentator in *AFL Evolution* alongside Dennis Cometti.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Richardson also works for Richmond's media department, presenting their ‘*Talking Tigers*’ weekly podcast show and other videos on the club's website.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] In September 2017, Richardson became a father for the first time when partner Genevieve Holliday gave birth to their daughter Zoey.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] The same month, Richardson worked the 2017 Grand Final pitting Richmond against Adelaide as a boundary rider and presented the Premiership cup to Richmond captain Trent Cotchin and coach Damien Hardwick following the Tigers' victory.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] The following year, Richardson and fellow Richmond legend Kevin Bartlett featured on an official recording of *We're From Tigerland*.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] His sister, Samantha, was married to retired Hawthorn, Western Bulldogs and North Melbourne footballer Jade Rawlings.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Matthew also has an older sister, Tracey, and a younger brother, Andrew.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] In April 2017, Matthew Richardson and fiancée of eight years, Genevieve Holliday, announced they were expecting their first child a daughter.
[src:matthew-richardson-footballer/matthew-richardson-footballer] Their daughter, Zoey Isabella Richardson was born on Sunday 3 September 2017.
